Flight from Moscow
The fall of communism gave the nations of the former Soviet bloc the chance to turn towards democracy, the market economy and the rule of law.
Some of these countries decisively broke ties with their communist past; others were less successful, and a few have catastrophically failed.
Moldova and Georgia belonged to the latter category until recently.
Their economic and political failure largely resulted from – Russia actively supporting – secessionist movements that tried to keep both countries within the "sphere of influence" of the Kremlin.
As bloody conflicts broke out in Transnistria, Abkhazia and South Ossetia, Russia transformed its military presence there into "peacekeeping forces" to maintain control.
For a long time, it was feared that these so-called "frozen conflicts" might suddenly turn hot.
Not only has this not happened, but we can now speak of solutions – for both Georgia and Moldova have begun to achieve breakthroughs towards a market economy and democracy.
This was also contributed to by the "neighborhood policy" of the European Union.
The starting point of these developments was the "Rose Revolution" in Georgia three years ago.
Already dangerously close to a failed state, Georgia has since turned towards the West.
The success of various "Color Revolutions" in former Soviet countries also triggered a change in Moldova. Here, President Vladimir Voronin initiated reforms aimed at closer alignment with the EU.
These changes have launched new initiatives in Georgia and Moldova to restore the territorial integrity of these countries in a peaceful manner.
The experience of Estonia suggests how Georgia and Moldova should shape their policy towards Russia.
When Estonia gained independence in 1991, Moscow sought to portray it as a country with enormous economic problems, unsuitable for investments.
Estland was indeed poor, and its most important exports were scrap metal and wood, yet its economy grew.
In North-East Estonia, with its predominantly Russian population, which had settled here during the Soviet era, Russia supported a so-called "autonomy movement."
When Estonia resisted, Russia imposed sanctions and halted gas deliveries.
On the few Estonian products that were allowed to be imported into Russia, high taxes were imposed, and Russia even threatened military intervention.
But Estonia kept its composure.
The Russian sanctions even helped the country to reorient its economy towards the West.
West Europe, on the other hand, did what it could to integrate the Baltic states – Latvia, Lithuania and Estonia – and at the same time tried to avoid a conflict with Russia.
In 1994, a free trade agreement with the EU enabled Estonian products to find new markets, and so Estonia ultimately became one of the most successful post-communist transition countries and joined the EU and NATO in 2004.
When Georgia became independent in 1991, it was not supported in the same way by Western Europe.
Indeed, Georgia appeared less attractive as a partner than the Baltic states; the 1990s were marked by coups, counter-coups and civil wars, with two regions – Abkhazia and South Ossetia – effectively seceding with the support of Russia.
The country has done its best to forget its bleak past.
Since the Rose Revolution, the economy has been reformed, the army has been strengthened, and the leadership of the country is young, dynamic, and diligently working to advance the nation.
Thanks to Georgia's flat income tax of 12% – probably the lowest in the world – the national budget has increased.
The government has raised pensions and increased social benefits.
Corruption is decreasing, and a judicial reform has been initiated.
The economy grew by 8% in 2005 and over 10% in 2006.
Georgia is trying to ease tensions around Abkhazia and South Ossetia; however, Russia accuses the country of aggression as well as ethnic cleansing.
His main goal is to prevent the West from supporting Georgia and to block reconciliation with the separatist regions.
The powers that matter in Georgia are Russia and to some extent the United States.
Europe must show that it is also significant.
Estland has shown – with its independence and again during the recent crisis over the relocation of a Soviet-era monument – that one can resist Russian pressure with determination and strong support.
Europe must understand that Georgia needs trade, not humanitarian aid.
Just as the free trade agreement with Europe enabled Estonia to find new markets, this can be the means by which Georgians can help themselves.
Georgia has just cause for hope that it will achieve real independence. But what about Moldova, the poorest country in Europe, which is more strongly threatened by Russia than the Estonians or even the Georgians ever were?
The lack of reform successes is partly the result of secessionist movements supported by Russia.
Dass sich die industrialisierte Region Transnistrien – deren russisch und ukrainisch sprechende Bevölkerung fürchtete, die Mehrheit der Moldauer, die rumänischer Abstammung ist, plane engere Verbindungen zu Rumänien – von Moldau lossagte, hat der Unabhängigkeit des Landes gleich zu Beginn einen schweren Schlag versetzt.
Es folgte ein Bürgerkrieg, und im Jahre 1992 marschierten russische Truppen in Transnistrien ein, wo sie heute noch sind.
Die Unabhängigkeit Transnistriens wurde nie anerkannt – weder von Moldau noch international.
Es heißt, dort herrsche Gesetzlosigkeit und Korruption.
Moldau ist hochverschuldet, die Arbeitslosigkeit ist hoch, und seine einst renommierte Weinbranche befindet sich im Niedergang.
Russia occasionally blocks gas deliveries, and many of the four million citizens have left the country.
Only Russia can solve the problem.
Moldovan government representatives have made four fruitless visits to Moscow to persuade President Vladimir Putin to try to find a solution and withdraw the Russian troops.
A desperate Voronin has asked the EU observer force Eubam for help, but an EU initiative would require Russian cooperation.
Unfortunately, it seems the West lacks current knowledge about the situation in Moldova.
For example, in April, the EU and also the USA only learned of a proposed peace agreement through a leaked report from Germany.
This, it seems, would benefit Russia, as Moldova is supposed to recognize Transnistria as a legitimate entity within it.
If Russia has thus outmaneuvered the West in this way, it would be a disastrous precedent for Georgia and other weak post-communist states.
